# OpenVPN3 GUI

A production-quality, native GNOME (GTK4 + Libadwaita) graphical frontend for
[openvpn3-linux](https://github.com/OpenVPN/openvpn3-linux). Every capability
of the `openvpn3` CLI — configurations, sessions, logs, ACLs, authentication,
statistics — exposed through a polished, HIG-compliant desktop application.
No terminal required.

![Ubuntu 24.04+](https://img.shields.io/badge/Ubuntu-24.04%2B-orange)
![Python 3.12+](https://img.shields.io/badge/Python-3.12%2B-blue)
![GTK4 + Libadwaita](https://img.shields.io/badge/GTK-4%20%2B%20Libadwaita-green)
![License GPL-3.0](https://img.shields.io/badge/License-GPL--3.0-lightgrey)

## Features

**Dashboard** — connection status, connected profile/server, public & VPN IP,
session duration, upload/download totals, a live Cairo-drawn bandwidth graph,
DNS servers, gateway, protocol, latency, and tunnel interface state, plus a
continuously updated system-health panel (openvpn3 service, D-Bus, internet,
tunnel).

**Profile Manager** — import/export `.ovpn` files (or fetch from a URL),
unlimited profiles, rename/duplicate/delete with confirmation, live
search/filter, four sort modes, favorites, tags, notes, last-used tracking,
embedded certificate inspection with expiry warnings, and full
`config-acl` management (public access, per-user grants, lock-down).

**Connection Manager** — connect/disconnect/reconnect/pause/resume, per-session
auto-restart toggle, multiple simultaneous sessions, a live connection
transcript, and an in-app connection history.

**Authentication** — interactive username/password, certificate,
PKCS#11 PIN, and MFA/OTP challenges are detected on the `session-start`
stream and answered through native dialogs. Credentials can optionally be
saved in the **GNOME Keyring (Secret Service)** — never on disk, never in
plaintext.

**Live Logs** — real-time tail of the openvpn3 log service and the app's own
structured logs, severity coloring, plain-text and **regex** filtering,
debug-verbosity toggle, copy to clipboard, and export to file.

**Session View** — every active session with PID, status, owner, interface,
routes, DNS, restart count, and per-session disconnect/restart controls.

**Network** — tunnel interface, MTU, IPv4/IPv6 addresses, pushed routes,
traffic statistics, plus built-in **public IP checker**, **latency test**,
and **DNS leak test**.

**Notifications** — native GNOME notifications for connect, disconnect,
errors, authentication requests, reconnects, and certificate expiry — each
individually toggleable.

**Tray** — StatusNotifierItem/AppIndicator icon with live status, quick
connect for favorite profiles, disconnect-all, and hide-to-tray on close.

**Automation** — connect on login (XDG autostart), connect on boot
(generated systemd user unit), reconnect when the network comes back
(NetworkManager D-Bus), reconnect on resume from suspend (logind D-Bus), and
cron-style scheduled reconnects. Pre/post connect/disconnect **hook scripts**
with custom environment variables and persisted execution logs.

**Developer Console** — every executed CLI command with stdout/stderr, exit
code, and duration; manual command execution routed through the same safe
wrapper (never a shell).

**More** — global search across profiles/sessions/settings/commands
(Ctrl+F), keyboard shortcuts, dark/light/system theme, localization
(gettext), settings import/export, full **backup/restore** archives,
per-profile **traffic history**, and a **plugin system**.

## Screenshot tour

Sidebar navigation: Dashboard · Profiles · Connections · Sessions ·
Live Logs · Network · Settings · Developer Console.

## Quick start

```bash
# 1. Install openvpn3-linux (the backend this GUI drives)
sudo apt install openvpn3

# 2. Install the GUI (Debian package)
sudo apt install ./openvpn3-gui_0.1.0-1_all.deb

# 3. Launch
openvpn3-gui
```

See [docs/INSTALL.md](docs/INSTALL.md) for Flatpak, AppImage, and
from-source instructions, [docs/USER_GUIDE.md](docs/USER_GUIDE.md) for a
feature walkthrough, and [docs/ARCHITECTURE.md](docs/ARCHITECTURE.md) +
[docs/DEVELOPER.md](docs/DEVELOPER.md) if you want to hack on it.

## Security posture

- The GUI **never runs as root and never invokes sudo**. All privileged
  tunnel operations are delegated to the openvpn3-linux D-Bus system
  services, which enforce their own **PolicyKit** actions
  (`net.openvpn.v3.*`).
- Secrets live exclusively in the **GNOME Keyring** via the Secret Service
  API. Backups deliberately exclude credentials.
- Subprocesses are spawned with argument vectors (`exec`, never a shell) —
  there is no shell-injection surface.
- Destructive actions (remove profile, disconnect, revoke access) always
  require an explicit confirmation dialog.

## Keyboard shortcuts

| Shortcut | Action |
|---|---|
| `Ctrl+F` | Global search |
| `Ctrl+1…5` | Dashboard / Profiles / Connections / Sessions / Logs |
| `Ctrl+,` | Settings |
| `Ctrl+Shift+D` | Developer Console |
| `Ctrl+Q` | Quit |

